1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:20,000
Okay, we're still in the domain number 6, which is testing and assessment.

2
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:40,000
We're still in the domain number 6, which is testing and assessment.

3
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:46,000
This section here talks about how security will be collecting certain types of information

4
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:50,000
that we need to provide assurance to stakeholders.

5
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:59,000
And the theme of this is that we may be collecting very technical information related to certain things that security does.

6
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:09,000
But the bottom line is that we're going to need to translate that into language that the stakeholders and our audience wants to hear it in.

7
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:13,000
Always based on goals and objectives of the organization itself.

8
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:17,000
And Rob's going to tell us what smart metrics are.

9
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:22,000
Yeah, I'm sure if you've ever had to do an employee performance review, you've come across this horrible acronym.

10
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:26,000
And you don't have to memorize smart metrics for the exam, but it highlights what we're talking about here,

11
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:30,000
which is when you want to be able to tell someone is the testing we're doing going well,

12
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:32,000
is the system operating effectively.

13
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:35,000
You've got to think very carefully about what metric data do you collect.

14
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:37,000
And this is where you have this idea of smart.

15
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:39,000
Is the metric data very specific?

16
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:42,000
Is it measurable? Is it actionable? Is it relevant? Is it timely?

17
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:47,000
You've got to think very carefully about what metrics you're collecting and what they'll tell people.

18
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:52,000
Because I'm sure you've seen this. There's plenty of examples where you can collect useless metrics.

19
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:56,000
Would it be useful if the CEO asked, how secure is our environment?

20
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:00,000
And you said, oh well, we've had 7 billion hits against our firewall.

21
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:02,000
Would that tell the CEO anything?

22
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:09,000
No, you have to translate into terms that relate to risk and exposure to the organization, for example.

23
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:10,000
Exactly.

24
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:14,000
Now, one bit of terminology that you need to know about are these different key indicators.

25
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:17,000
And there's two. There is key performance indicators.

26
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:21,000
And there's key risk indicators, KPIs and KRIs.

27
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:24,000
And here's a really simple way that I found to think about these, okay?

28
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:26,000
Because it sounds kind of confusing.

29
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:29,000
Key performance indicators are backward looking.

30
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:35,000
And by that, I mean, by looking backwards, you can say, did we actually achieve the performance goals that we were looking to meet?

31
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:39,000
Like if we said, we're going to go and do this thing, we're going to spend this money on this, we're going to do this that and the other thing.

32
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:43,000
KPIs look backwards and say, did we actually achieve that?

33
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:47,000
And then KRIs, key risk indicators, are forward looking.

34
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:50,000
This is where you say things like, you know, these are the risks that we're worried about occurring.

35
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:54,000
That might happen. These are the things that could potentially happen.

36
00:02:54,000 --> 00:02:58,000
And KRIs are how you measure to see, look forward and say, are these things actually occurring?

37
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:00,000
And that's the key difference between those two.

38
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:05,000
Yeah. And again, important to relate these to goals and objectives of the organization.

39
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:19,000
In fact, sometimes, you know, even though we're talking KPIs and KRIs, we need to relate these to KGIs, which are key goal indicators that upper management to CEO, the Board of Directors, would be really interested in.

40
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:21,000
Exactly.

41
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:24,000
Now, can we ever measure everything?

42
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:31,000
Can we know, yeah, I mean, can we ever measure anything? And the answer, of course, is no.

43
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:34,000
So how do we decide to what to focus our metrics on?

44
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:47,000
Well, good answer would always be value, but if we understand the goals and objectives of the organization, then, you know, and if we involve those people at that level, they're going to tell us what they're interested in measuring.

45
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:53,000
And that's what we, security professionals and what security does, should put priority on.

46
00:03:53,000 --> 00:04:01,000
Always measuring things in terms of goals and objectives of the organization and what's meaningful to those people at that level.

47
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:07,000
Yeah, I mean, whatever the organization is trying to achieve, we should be figuring out how we can show, develop metrics that we're going to show.

48
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:12,000
Are we actually getting there? That's a perfect example of how we align security with overall business goals and objectives.

49
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:16,000
Yeah, we've got some examples here on the next slide.

50
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:28,000
But, you know, the point that we're trying to make here is when you look at some of these, they may be at the technical level that may need others to be able to translate into goals and objectives of the organization.

51
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:40,000
So this is an area that I think security has struggled with in the past, but that's because we've always had that bottom-up approach to security, and that makes it difficult to try and relate to goals and objectives.

52
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:49,000
The answer to this is top-down, and if those people are involved in what security does, it becomes easy in measuring what they're interested in.

53
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:51,000
Yeah, and different stakeholders are going to want to know different things.

54
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:57,000
So backup verification is an example. You would never tell the CEO how many of the backups have been verified correctly.

55
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:00,000
But the person that's in charge of backups, they'd want to know that.

56
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:04,000
So the metrics are going to vary depending on who you're reporting them to, and that's just all we want to show with this slide.

57
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:12,000
Speak the audience's language, which means based on what they want to hear, based on what they are accountable for, goals and objectives.

58
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:14,000
Metrics, it doesn't matter.

